Apparently `PyUnicode_FromUnicode` has been deprecated. We hit the `PyUnicode_FromUnicode(NULL, 0)` call in [__Pyx_decode_c_string](https://github.com/cython/cython/blob/0.29.20/Cython/Utility/StringTools.c#L470) in NumPy, xref numpy/numpy#16640

Edit: The [recommended interface](https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0393/#string-creation) is `PyUnicode_New(Py_ssize_t size, Py_UCS4 maxchar)`;

Edit: already fixed on master, but not in 0.29.20 nor in 3.0a5

Ok, I had to start over with the Unicode C-API changes. The previous implementation was merging spelled-out surrogates in Py3 code. 13eb4498b70c947cd1bb972dcf4ebd75f609d3e4 now uses the `unicode_escape` codec to store surrogates, because that seems to be the only codec that can pass them through. The caveat is still that it generates different code on Py2 16-bit Unicode platforms.

I would not normally introduce a breaking change like this in the 0.29.x release series (it would be a clear 3.0 change), but since everyone is shouting "support 3.9! support 3.9!", and since many projects have already dropped Py2 support, I'm valuing Py3.9 support higher than Py2.[67] support on Windows here. (Already waiting for the corresponding bug report to come in…)

@hroncok, could you please rerun the Fedora builds with the latest branch? Thanks!
